00:11:58.990 --> 00:11:59.770
It's done, right?

00:11:59.770 --> 00:12:03.080
BRIAN LEROUX: I wish it was.

00:12:03.080 --> 00:12:05.034
I think it depends
on your app content

00:12:05.034 --> 00:12:06.450
and what you're
trying to do, what

00:12:06.450 --> 00:12:08.241
you're trying to achieve
with that content.

00:12:08.241 --> 00:12:10.500
If you've got something
that's more text heavy

00:12:10.500 --> 00:12:13.320
and needs to be updated
frequently then responsive

00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:14.600
websites make a lot of sense.

00:12:14.600 --> 00:12:16.308
As soon as you start
having interactivity

00:12:16.308 --> 00:12:18.710
that involves the
sensors of the phone,

00:12:18.710 --> 00:12:20.040
the web's kind of a ghetto.

00:12:20.040 --> 00:12:22.570
And then if you need
that thing to be offline,

00:12:22.570 --> 00:12:24.442
you well know that
that can be difficult.

00:12:24.442 --> 00:12:25.900
The trick is,
though, people always

00:12:25.900 --> 00:12:27.250
say that native's
better at offline.

00:12:27.250 --> 00:12:28.333
I don't think that's true.

00:12:28.333 --> 00:12:31.760
Like this morning I was trying
to get into Uber and I'm with

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:33.640
T-Mobile so I couldn't.

00:12:33.640 --> 00:12:37.122
Because effectively I was
offline even I said it was on.

00:12:37.122 --> 00:12:38.026
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:38.026 --> 00:12:40.790
And Uber works really poorly
when you're not online.

00:12:40.790 --> 00:12:42.440
And that's the case
with a lot of apps.

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:45.160
So I don't know that offline
is actually a native advantage,

00:12:45.160 --> 00:12:46.790
it's just a programming style.

00:12:46.790 --> 00:12:49.345
And the web style just
happens to be really hostile.

00:12:49.345 --> 00:12:51.470
JAKE ARCHIBALD: And working
with the offline stuff,

00:12:51.470 --> 00:12:53.955
I find that it's only the
very best of native apps

00:12:53.955 --> 00:12:56.676
that seem to do this stuff
well, very few of them.

00:12:56.676 --> 00:12:58.300
So what kind of stuff
do you see people

00:12:58.300 --> 00:13:01.462
using PhoneGap for today?

00:13:01.462 --> 00:13:03.420
BRIAN LEROUX: They us if
for all kinds of stuff

00:13:03.420 --> 00:13:04.900
they probably
shouldn't use it for.

00:13:04.900 --> 00:13:06.275
And they use it
for stuff that we

00:13:06.275 --> 00:13:07.800
don't expect them to use it for.

00:13:07.800 --> 00:13:11.860
The big trend lately for us
has been in the enterprise.

00:13:11.860 --> 00:13:14.500
A lot of business apps
are being built now.

00:13:14.500 --> 00:13:17.690
The larger corporations
that are out there invested

00:13:17.690 --> 00:13:19.600
all this money and all
this infrastructure

00:13:19.600 --> 00:13:21.420
in the web and then
suddenly everyone's

00:13:21.420 --> 00:13:22.810
showing up with iPhones.

00:13:22.810 --> 00:13:26.080
And they've got a whole bunch
of Java programmers in the back

00:13:26.080 --> 00:13:28.330
there, slaving away
on SQL and they

00:13:28.330 --> 00:13:31.220
don't want to learn Objective
C. And they see Swift,

00:13:31.220 --> 00:13:33.810
and they're like, OK, maybe
that's going to be OK.

00:13:33.810 --> 00:13:37.860
Except for, it only works on
iOS8 and it won't work on iOS9.

00:13:37.860 --> 00:13:39.584
So Swift is probably
not something

00:13:39.584 --> 00:13:41.500
you want to invest in
if you're an enterprise.

00:13:41.500 --> 00:13:43.950
So they're looking to the
web technologies as a way

00:13:43.950 --> 00:13:44.800
to solve this.

00:13:44.800 --> 00:13:49.094
So that seems to be the place
that we're the most popularity.

00:13:49.094 --> 00:13:51.510
JAKE ARCHIBALD: You're doing
similar things on BlackBerry,

00:13:51.510 --> 00:13:55.830
taking the web stuff and
app-ifying onto that platform.

00:13:55.830 --> 00:13:57.782
Are you seeing the
same kind of trends?

00:13:57.782 --> 00:13:58.740
ELI FIDLER: Absolutely.

00:13:58.740 --> 00:14:00.950
I mean, we have our
WebWorks platform,

00:14:00.950 --> 00:14:04.205
which is essentially a
wrapper around Cordova.

00:14:04.205 --> 00:14:08.840
And a huge, huge number of apps
for all BlackBerry platforms

00:14:08.840 --> 00:14:11.050
are written using
this technology.

00:14:11.050 --> 00:14:13.930
I think it's compelling
for application developers

00:14:13.930 --> 00:14:16.190
because lots of people
have web skills.

00:14:16.190 --> 00:14:20.340
And you can argue semantics
about what is the web,

00:14:20.340 --> 00:14:22.790
and how is an app the
web or not the web.

00:14:22.790 --> 00:14:26.900
But even if it's not
online in a browser,

00:14:26.900 --> 00:14:29.290
people know HTML and
JavaScript and CSS,

00:14:29.290 --> 00:14:31.102
and those technologies,
independent

00:14:31.102 --> 00:14:32.810
of a lot of the other
problems that we've

00:14:32.810 --> 00:14:35.450
talked about have won
in a lot of cases.

00:14:35.450 --> 00:14:40.110
Even apps that we consider
native often have,

00:14:40.110 --> 00:14:43.040
most of the app, or at least
a huge percentage of the app

00:14:43.040 --> 00:14:44.000
is a web view.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:45.041
BRIAN LEROUX: App stores.

00:14:46.954 --> 00:14:49.370
JAKE ARCHIBALD: Is that why--
because you mentioned before

00:14:49.370 --> 00:14:53.910
that people are building
PhoneGap style things for stuff

00:14:53.910 --> 00:14:56.200
they probably shouldn't.

00:14:56.200 --> 00:14:57.190
Is app stores why?

00:14:57.190 --> 00:14:58.393
BRIAN LEROUX: I shouldn't
of said that, but--

00:14:58.393 --> 00:14:59.240
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:59.240 --> 00:15:00.610
I can't that one back now.

00:15:00.610 --> 00:15:03.540
So like, for example, one of
the big ones we see is games.

00:15:03.540 --> 00:15:05.800
We see a lot of people
building games using web tech.

00:15:05.800 --> 00:15:08.258
And I guess when you're a young
programmer, when you're new

00:15:08.258 --> 00:15:10.412
or you're amateur and you
want to get into software

00:15:10.412 --> 00:15:12.870
development, one of the things
that becomes really exciting

00:15:12.870 --> 00:15:13.690
is games.

00:15:13.690 --> 00:15:16.640
And so we've been
saying for years,

00:15:16.640 --> 00:15:19.390
don't build a game on PhoneGap,
that's a terrible idea.

00:15:19.390 --> 00:15:22.470
You need delay, and have high
intensive graphics and stuff.

00:15:22.470 --> 00:15:24.570
But it terms in mobile
that you don't actually

00:15:24.570 --> 00:15:26.870
need high intensive
graphics and stuff.

00:15:26.870 --> 00:15:30.120
Like Sudoku type games,
like little card games,

00:15:30.120 --> 00:15:31.620
really simple 2D platformers.

00:15:31.620 --> 00:15:34.161
And for that type of thing the
web is actually really good at

00:15:34.161 --> 00:15:35.190
and it's getting better.

00:15:35.190 --> 00:15:36.790
So that's the type of
thing where we're like,

00:15:36.790 --> 00:15:37.956
don't use PhoneGap for that.

00:15:37.956 --> 00:15:40.332
But people do anyways.

00:15:40.332 --> 00:15:41.790
JAKE ARCHIBALD:
Dominic [INAUDIBLE]

00:15:41.790 --> 00:15:44.110
has a point about that?

00:15:44.110 --> 00:15:46.050
DOMINIC: Yeah, I
guess I'm just not

00:15:46.050 --> 00:15:48.580
as interested in
using HTML and CSS,

00:15:48.580 --> 00:15:50.419
and so on, just as a
programming language.

00:15:50.419 --> 00:15:51.710
There's all these technologies.

00:15:51.710 --> 00:15:54.380
You can use C Sharp and you
can use all these things

00:15:54.380 --> 00:15:56.580
that compile to whatever's
native on the platform

00:15:56.580 --> 00:15:57.960
or get baked in.

00:15:57.960 --> 00:16:00.160
What I'm most interested
in is how do we get it

00:16:00.160 --> 00:16:01.750
so I don't have to
go through Apple

00:16:01.750 --> 00:16:04.125
and submit to their app store
and go through their review

00:16:04.125 --> 00:16:05.511
process?

00:16:05.511 --> 00:16:07.760
Because I don't want to just
use the web technologies,

00:16:07.760 --> 00:16:09.510
I want to get all the
benefits of the web.

00:16:11.915 --> 00:16:14.040
BRIAN LEROUX: There's an
answer that I can give you

00:16:14.040 --> 00:16:15.590
when I'm not being recorded.

00:16:15.590 --> 00:16:17.807
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:17.807 --> 00:16:19.640
MATT ANDREWS: So right
now, your only choice

00:16:19.640 --> 00:16:20.973
is to add to home screen, right?

00:16:20.973 --> 00:16:24.230
You can build a single page app
or even a not to single page

00:16:24.230 --> 00:16:27.680
app if you had hijacking
links and doing

00:16:27.680 --> 00:16:29.970
horrible things like that.

00:16:29.970 --> 00:16:33.020
And that's your only choice.

00:16:33.020 --> 00:16:35.510
I think the spec,
the manifest spec

00:16:35.510 --> 00:16:37.080
will hopefully improve that.

00:16:41.140 --> 00:16:42.940
MARCOS CACERES: So
yeah, the manifest spec

00:16:42.940 --> 00:16:44.810
is attempting to address that.

00:16:44.810 --> 00:16:47.380
So it's trying to-- those
things that I mentioned before,

00:16:47.380 --> 00:16:49.390
that list of things
that we need-- it's

00:16:49.390 --> 00:16:52.000
trying to address those things.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:55.030
But again, it requires
everybody to get on board.

00:16:55.030 --> 00:16:57.450
If we can't get all the
browser vendors on board,

00:16:57.450 --> 00:16:59.004
then it's like--

00:16:59.004 --> 00:17:00.670
JAKE ARCHIBALD: So
who is on board then?

00:17:00.670 --> 00:17:03.151
Chrome, Opera, Mozilla?

00:17:03.151 --> 00:17:04.650
MARCOS CACERES:
Opera not explicitly

00:17:04.650 --> 00:17:08.849
but they may get it
straight from Blink.

00:17:08.849 --> 00:17:09.970
Who knows about Apple.

00:17:09.970 --> 00:17:12.530
Microsoft has kind of said,
yeah, we're kind of interested.

00:17:12.530 --> 00:17:13.446
It looks kind of cool.

00:17:13.446 --> 00:17:15.291
But they haven't
committed to anything.

00:17:15.291 --> 00:17:17.040
JAKE ARCHIBALD: So can
we get a microphone

00:17:17.040 --> 00:17:18.119
to-- Matthew
Hoffman, do you want

00:17:18.119 --> 00:17:19.702
to raise your hand
where ever you are.

00:17:19.702 --> 00:17:20.630
You're over there.

00:17:20.630 --> 00:17:24.010
And Andrew, I don't have a
screen with that on here.

00:17:24.010 --> 00:17:27.060
So it's kind of difficult for
me to see who's in the queue.

00:17:27.060 --> 00:17:28.530
I don't know if that solvable.

00:17:28.530 --> 00:17:30.172
If not, don't worry about it.

00:17:30.172 --> 00:17:32.630
MATTHEW HOFFMAN: So I think
one of the problems of web apps

00:17:32.630 --> 00:17:37.240
on mobile is that they cannot
actually integrate fully with

00:17:37.240 --> 00:17:43.610
the native UI that the
mobile platforms provide.

00:17:43.610 --> 00:17:47.150
So it's two islands really, and
you can call in some features,

00:17:47.150 --> 00:17:49.850
but you cannot show anything
coming from native inside

00:17:49.850 --> 00:17:50.800
your web app island.

00:17:53.315 --> 00:17:54.690
MARCOS CACERES:
What do you mean?

00:17:54.690 --> 00:17:54.850
Sorry.

00:17:54.850 --> 00:17:56.141
What do you mean in particular?

00:18:02.630 --> 00:18:04.290
MATTHEW HOFFMAN: Any contents.

00:18:04.290 --> 00:18:06.185
For example, video
produced from native.

00:18:06.185 --> 00:18:09.620
And possibly if you have UI
elements that you want to make

00:18:09.620 --> 00:18:14.620
your web app feel more native,
you cannot do that either.

00:18:14.620 --> 00:18:19.050
So you can leverage
sensors and all that,

00:18:19.050 --> 00:18:23.250
but you cannot build something
that looks and feels native

00:18:23.250 --> 00:18:25.680
in the web.

00:18:25.680 --> 00:18:27.890
MARCOS CACERES: So can
I bounce to Brian here.

00:18:27.890 --> 00:18:32.140
Because for PhoneGap, you're
targeting cross platform.

00:18:32.140 --> 00:18:36.200
And I would have imagined
that if you're actually

00:18:36.200 --> 00:18:38.400
building an app you want
it to have, more or less,

00:18:38.400 --> 00:18:40.390
its own look and feel.

00:18:40.390 --> 00:18:42.830
Of course leverage what
you can from the OS,

00:18:42.830 --> 00:18:43.804
but across the board?

00:18:43.804 --> 00:18:45.220
BRIAN LEROUX: The
first six months

00:18:45.220 --> 00:18:48.870
of PhoneGap's life we definitely
experimented with plug-ins,

00:18:48.870 --> 00:18:51.690
which would abstract
out user interfaces.

00:18:51.690 --> 00:18:54.750
So that you could do things
like invoke a tab bar.

00:18:54.750 --> 00:18:56.980
Those metaphors
got really leaky.

00:18:56.980 --> 00:18:58.332
And they broke down super fast.

00:18:58.332 --> 00:19:00.040
And you probably have
seen that if you've

00:19:00.040 --> 00:19:02.070
used any kind of
compiled to solutions.

00:19:02.070 --> 00:19:05.710
So a tab bar on iOS isn't the
same as a tab bar on Android.

00:19:05.710 --> 00:19:07.850
[INAUDIBLE] on iOS is
usually on the bottom.

00:19:07.850 --> 00:19:11.280
And sometimes the iOS one
has bevels and embosses.

00:19:11.280 --> 00:19:12.950
Not anymore but it used to.

00:19:12.950 --> 00:19:15.140
And so then you'd end up
having to kind of reinvent

00:19:15.140 --> 00:19:17.170
CSS for this damn
tab bar and you

00:19:17.170 --> 00:19:20.090
don't want to do that either
because there's already CSS.

00:19:20.090 --> 00:19:22.920
And so the web
has sort of shown,

00:19:22.920 --> 00:19:25.800
and there's lots of
projects out that

00:19:25.800 --> 00:19:28.290
demonstrate that you can
build native like interfaces.

00:19:28.290 --> 00:19:30.840
And I say native-like, I
won't say a native interfaces.

00:19:30.840 --> 00:19:34.910
So like Ionic, Polymer
with material design

00:19:34.910 --> 00:19:37.240
is actually looking
really good on Android.

00:19:37.240 --> 00:19:40.780
Maybe not so much on iOS8 yet,
but soon it will, I'm sure.

00:19:40.780 --> 00:19:45.500
So I don't think it's
actually worth pursuing.

00:19:45.500 --> 00:19:47.730
We could waste our
time trying to paint

00:19:47.730 --> 00:19:51.620
over Android's UI and
iOS' UI and create

00:19:51.620 --> 00:19:54.500
some kind of universal UI
that everybody opts into it

00:19:54.500 --> 00:19:55.960
and loves and it native.

00:19:55.960 --> 00:19:57.661
Or we can just do
the stuff ourselves

00:19:57.661 --> 00:19:58.660
with the web primitives.

00:19:58.660 --> 00:20:02.277
And I think the extensible web
manifesto type discussion later

00:20:02.277 --> 00:20:03.610
will touch into that a lot more.

00:20:03.610 --> 00:20:05.895
We need these lower
level paint kind ideas

00:20:05.895 --> 00:20:08.265
so that we can build these
properties and interfaces.

00:20:08.265 --> 00:20:10.890
I think native
interfaces themselves,

00:20:10.890 --> 00:20:12.667
the abstractions
are just too leaky.

00:20:12.667 --> 00:20:15.250
If you want to build an iOS app
and have it be native, pick up

00:20:15.250 --> 00:20:17.340
a book on Objective C.

00:20:17.340 --> 00:20:19.923
JAKE ARCHIBALD: I know some of
the custom layout stuff, that's

00:20:19.923 --> 00:20:22.180
going to come up in the
[INAUDIBLE] panel as well.

00:20:22.180 --> 00:20:24.040
Can we get Dominic a
microphone and we'll

00:20:24.040 --> 00:20:25.695
wrap up this question?

00:20:25.695 --> 00:20:28.070
DOMINIC: Yeah I just wanted
to share an interesting point

00:20:28.070 --> 00:20:31.240
that we ran into on
the Polymer team.

00:20:31.240 --> 00:20:35.020
When the material
design stuff came out,

00:20:35.020 --> 00:20:37.180
we were seeing articles
where it's like,

00:20:37.180 --> 00:20:40.400
is the paper element,
the custom element close

00:20:40.400 --> 00:20:41.760
to the Android version?

00:20:41.760 --> 00:20:44.070
As if the Android
version was canonical.

00:20:44.070 --> 00:20:45.590
But really, the
team was asking, why

00:20:45.590 --> 00:20:47.840
does everybody think the
Android version is canonical?

00:20:47.840 --> 00:20:49.215
It might as well
just be the case

00:20:49.215 --> 00:20:52.010
that the version we're putting
out for the web is canonical

00:20:52.010 --> 00:20:53.510
and you should be
comparing to that.

00:20:53.510 --> 00:20:56.650
So I kind of agree that
maybe it doesn't matter,

00:20:56.650 --> 00:21:00.004
but also, it's like, the web
is a first class programming

00:21:00.004 --> 00:21:01.420
platform for all
these things too,

00:21:01.420 --> 00:21:03.194
so I thought that
was interesting.

00:21:03.194 --> 00:21:04.610
JAKE ARCHIBALD:
That kind of leads

00:21:04.610 --> 00:21:06.200
nicely into the next question.

00:21:06.200 --> 00:21:08.170
Or certainly in
terms of maybe not

00:21:08.170 --> 00:21:10.190
taking Android's lead on things.

00:21:10.190 --> 00:21:11.930
So this question's
from Andrew Betts,

00:21:11.930 --> 00:21:13.600
I don't you've heard of him.

00:21:13.600 --> 00:21:17.450
He says, "the web model of
granular on-demand user consent

00:21:17.450 --> 00:21:20.520
is the only sensible way
of doing app permissions.

00:21:20.520 --> 00:21:22.380
Why do app packaging
systems rush

00:21:22.380 --> 00:21:25.120
to destroy that model
in favor of the broken

00:21:25.120 --> 00:21:26.527
up front permissions list?

00:21:26.527 --> 00:21:28.110
And I have a lot of
sympathy for this,

00:21:28.110 --> 00:21:30.180
because I know in the
Chrome web install,

00:21:30.180 --> 00:21:32.320
when TweetDeck's
there and there were

00:21:32.320 --> 00:21:34.490
a series of user
reviews saying, I

00:21:34.490 --> 00:21:37.030
don't trust this because
when I go to install it,

00:21:37.030 --> 00:21:41.220
it asks to be able to
tweet on my behalf.

00:21:41.220 --> 00:21:42.410
I don't want it to do that.

00:21:42.410 --> 00:21:43.250
That sounds crazy.

00:21:43.250 --> 00:21:44.708
But people didn't
realize that when

00:21:44.708 --> 00:21:47.300
you type in a box on
TweetDeck and you hit tweet,

00:21:47.300 --> 00:21:49.920
TweetDeck is tweeting on your
behalf, that's what it's doing.

00:21:49.920 --> 00:21:52.560
And it asks for permission at
that point it would make sense.

00:21:52.560 --> 00:21:55.816
So Chris, Google uses
this up front model

00:21:55.816 --> 00:21:56.940
for Chrome apps in Android.

00:21:56.940 --> 00:21:58.990
Why do we keep getting it wrong?

00:21:58.990 --> 00:22:02.350
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:02.350 --> 00:22:05.370
CHRIS WILSON: I think that
was a decision you made.

00:22:05.370 --> 00:22:09.230
No, I mean, I think the reason
why we keep doing this--

00:22:09.230 --> 00:22:12.000
and I won't say it's
wrong, necessarily.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:15.140
The reason why we keep doing
is it's seductively easy.

00:22:15.140 --> 00:22:18.000
You just pop something
up-- yeah 90% of the users

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:19.740
may not actually read it.

00:22:19.740 --> 00:22:24.220
99.999% of the users may not
read it, but they click OK.

00:22:24.220 --> 00:22:25.990
And then from the
app's perspective

00:22:25.990 --> 00:22:28.320
they get to do whatever
they needed to do.

00:22:28.320 --> 00:22:29.800
They get to do
whatever they want.

00:22:29.800 --> 00:22:31.210
This is not really good.

00:22:31.210 --> 00:22:33.570
I'm not saying this is
the right thing to do.

00:22:33.570 --> 00:22:35.990
But I think that we are
trying to do this better.

00:22:35.990 --> 00:22:40.800
The flow chart that Marcos
put up on the screen earlier

00:22:40.800 --> 00:22:43.290
