I'm going to direct
this question at Brian.

00:32:41.540 --> 00:32:43.430
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:43.430 --> 00:32:45.934
I think that came from
little Bobby Tables.

00:32:45.934 --> 00:32:47.830
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:47.830 --> 00:32:50.430
BRIAN LEROUX: I like that
they've done this HTML5 style

00:32:50.430 --> 00:32:52.750
without having to
quote their attributes.

00:32:52.750 --> 00:32:53.490
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:53.490 --> 00:32:54.270
It's a good style.

00:32:54.270 --> 00:32:56.270
JAKE ARCHIBALD: That's
actually from the future.

00:32:56.270 --> 00:32:56.880
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:56.880 --> 00:32:59.380
Well, we'll probably move on
from that to the next question.

00:32:59.380 --> 00:33:01.000
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:04.870
So this came from Connell,
who's provided actually

00:33:04.870 --> 00:33:06.370
a lot of the really
good questions

00:33:06.370 --> 00:33:09.220
for many of the panels, so
you'll get bored of his name

00:33:09.220 --> 00:33:12.360
soon. "Instead of asking for
permissions for small things,

00:33:12.360 --> 00:33:14.770
can browsers instead
infer a level of trust

00:33:14.770 --> 00:33:17.040
from other factors such
as usage frequency,

00:33:17.040 --> 00:33:19.710
whether it's from bookmarked
or reputation of the domain?"

00:33:19.710 --> 00:33:21.550
Chris, you're Google, right?

00:33:21.550 --> 00:33:23.060
Should Google
decide which domains

00:33:23.060 --> 00:33:25.230
get enhanced permissions
based on our ratings?

00:33:25.230 --> 00:33:26.980
Because that sounds
like the kind of thing

00:33:26.980 --> 00:33:28.500
the public would really love.

00:33:28.500 --> 00:33:29.541
CHRIS WILSON: Absolutely.

00:33:29.541 --> 00:33:30.980
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:30.980 --> 00:33:33.760
I think users will be
as delighted with that

00:33:33.760 --> 00:33:36.300
as they are to get ads that
are more applicable to them.

00:33:36.300 --> 00:33:38.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:38.540 --> 00:33:41.190
And I mean that completely.

00:33:41.190 --> 00:33:45.030
No, I mean I think that
we already, in some ways,

00:33:45.030 --> 00:33:48.080
we already do similar things.

00:33:48.080 --> 00:33:51.220
In that if you visit
a page with HTTPS

00:33:51.220 --> 00:33:54.382
and it asks for access to
the microphone, for example,

00:33:54.382 --> 00:33:56.340
the next time you visit
it, we don't ask again.

00:33:56.340 --> 00:33:59.040
We cache that, we
remember that you said OK,

00:33:59.040 --> 00:34:00.680
and it's a secure domain.

00:34:00.680 --> 00:34:03.190
"Secure" domain.

00:34:03.190 --> 00:34:07.440
I do think that there are
things in that question that

00:34:07.440 --> 00:34:12.000
make a small trickle of
sweat go down my spine.

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:15.250
So I won't say absolutely, we
should do all of these things.

00:34:15.250 --> 00:34:17.739
But I do think that being
more intelligent about how

00:34:17.739 --> 00:34:19.560
we can infer trust
from other things

00:34:19.560 --> 00:34:22.280
that the user has
said or done, as long

00:34:22.280 --> 00:34:26.100
as we can have a clear, secure
track back to the domain.

00:34:26.100 --> 00:34:29.280
I think that that's
probably the right future.

00:34:29.280 --> 00:34:31.082
But we're several
steps from there still.

00:34:31.082 --> 00:34:33.290
JAKE ARCHIBALD: So rather
than completely deciding it

00:34:33.290 --> 00:34:35.560
based on ratings, if
something like bookmarking

00:34:35.560 --> 00:34:38.940
was used as a signal, is that
something that sounds fair?

00:34:38.940 --> 00:34:39.808
CHRIS WILSON: Yeah.

00:34:39.808 --> 00:34:41.891
ELI FIDLER: Bookmarking
is used as a signal today.

00:34:41.891 --> 00:34:45.904
So if you saved a
home screen on iOS

00:34:45.904 --> 00:34:47.570
and then launch it
from the home screen,

00:34:47.570 --> 00:34:50.469
it can control mostly at
every pixel of the screen.

00:34:50.469 --> 00:34:52.820
That's not a
permission that we give

00:34:52.820 --> 00:34:54.279
to websites in the browser.

00:34:54.279 --> 00:34:56.070
JAKE ARCHIBALD: Hmm, true, true.

00:34:56.070 --> 00:34:58.350
What kind of permissions
would make sense

00:34:58.350 --> 00:34:59.890
to sort of auto-grant
for something

00:34:59.890 --> 00:35:03.180
that was added to the home
screen that wouldn't surprise

00:35:03.180 --> 00:35:04.772
a user that we've granted that?

00:35:04.772 --> 00:35:06.480
CHRIS WILSON: I think
that's a challenge.

00:35:06.480 --> 00:35:09.790
Because that's true, if
you add to home screen

00:35:09.790 --> 00:35:11.450
you get a bunch of extra rights.

00:35:11.450 --> 00:35:14.570
And I'll also say that I
think, add to home screen

00:35:14.570 --> 00:35:20.000
is the worst thing today because
it's buried in every mobile OS

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:21.070
that I've seen.

00:35:21.070 --> 00:35:24.280
And hard to find, hard to
discover for average users.

00:35:24.280 --> 00:35:26.470
I mean, I think in
Android, you have

00:35:26.470 --> 00:35:29.150
to click an icon that's
not at all intuitive

00:35:29.150 --> 00:35:32.860
and then it's like, at the very
bottom on my phone, where it's

00:35:32.860 --> 00:35:34.820
almost getting cut
off the screen.

00:35:34.820 --> 00:35:37.390
Which seems really bizarre for
something that I want to do.

00:35:37.390 --> 00:35:39.420
And as a user it's
not clear that when

00:35:39.420 --> 00:35:41.780
I click that I'm giving
additional rights.

00:35:41.780 --> 00:35:43.670
Like it means
something other than

00:35:43.670 --> 00:35:45.930
stick an icon on my
home screen somewhere.

00:35:45.930 --> 00:35:47.730
And that bit, I'm a
little worried about.

00:35:47.730 --> 00:35:49.070
How we explain that to users.

00:35:49.070 --> 00:35:53.947
That it's not install, it's not
this gigantic Android-esque,

00:35:53.947 --> 00:35:56.030
here are all the permissions
that you're magically

00:35:56.030 --> 00:35:56.710
getting now.

00:35:56.710 --> 00:35:59.380
Are you sure you're OK with
that, good, kind of thing.

00:35:59.380 --> 00:36:02.650
But it does also
somehow indicate

00:36:02.650 --> 00:36:04.517
to the user in an obvious way--

00:36:04.517 --> 00:36:06.100
MARCOS CACERES: But
this is like where

00:36:06.100 --> 00:36:08.680
Adrian's diagram
comes into play.

00:36:08.680 --> 00:36:12.140
Because adding to home
screen and getting

00:36:12.140 --> 00:36:15.039
all the pixels is
a minor annoyance.

00:36:15.039 --> 00:36:16.080
CHRIS WILSON: It is, yes.

00:36:16.080 --> 00:36:17.455
MARCOS CACERES:
So there is that.

00:36:17.455 --> 00:36:20.180
So maybe there shouldn't
be a permission for that?

00:36:20.180 --> 00:36:22.292
So again, it's trying to
find that balance and--

00:36:22.292 --> 00:36:24.000
BRIAN LEROUX: I think
the biggest problem

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:25.480
we've got right
now is that we've

00:36:25.480 --> 00:36:27.930
spent seven years
teaching people

00:36:27.930 --> 00:36:30.240
to install apps
from the app store.

00:36:30.240 --> 00:36:33.270
And we've spent seven years of
people thinking that discovery

00:36:33.270 --> 00:36:36.390
happens by going to Play
or going to an app store.

00:36:36.390 --> 00:36:38.480
And there's no-- I
guess the closest

00:36:38.480 --> 00:36:40.392
thing we have right
now is like, Google

00:36:40.392 --> 00:36:41.850
would be the app
store for the web.

00:36:41.850 --> 00:36:45.567
But there's no way for us
to say, OK, this is a thing,

00:36:45.567 --> 00:36:47.400
and this thing's going
to be on your device.

00:36:47.400 --> 00:36:49.500
And it's going to do
things that maybe you

00:36:49.500 --> 00:36:51.452
wouldn't want it
to do necessarily.

00:36:51.452 --> 00:36:53.910
JAKE ARCHIBALD: Can we get a
microphone to Guy, by the way.

00:36:53.910 --> 00:36:56.840
CHRIS WILSON: We've also spent
more than 20 years teaching

00:36:56.840 --> 00:36:59.040
people that everything on
the web is totally safe.

00:36:59.040 --> 00:37:00.281
And don't worry about it.

00:37:00.281 --> 00:37:00.780
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:00.780 --> 00:37:03.410
And now we're-- as Jake said
at the beginning, now there's--

00:37:03.410 --> 00:37:04.830
BRIAN LEROUX: As long as there's
a little lock, it's all good.

00:37:04.830 --> 00:37:05.720
CHRIS WILSON: Yeah.

00:37:05.720 --> 00:37:08.490
Even without the lock, you
can't do anything dangerous.

00:37:08.490 --> 00:37:10.240
GUY: I just wanted to
point out that there

00:37:10.240 --> 00:37:12.448
might be a difference between
the permissions of what

00:37:12.448 --> 00:37:13.350
we're talking about.

00:37:13.350 --> 00:37:15.683
So sometimes there are security
and privacy permissions.

00:37:15.683 --> 00:37:18.020
And also kind of
makes wet trickle down

00:37:18.020 --> 00:37:21.097
my spine to think that
Google would determine

00:37:21.097 --> 00:37:22.680
to give my location
away, or something

00:37:22.680 --> 00:37:24.850
like that based on usage.

00:37:24.850 --> 00:37:26.764
On the other hand,
things like resources,

00:37:26.764 --> 00:37:28.680
quota for local storage--
if everybody started

00:37:28.680 --> 00:37:31.407
using local storage of the
new service worker quota,

00:37:31.407 --> 00:37:33.490
you know, there would be
a problem for the agents.

00:37:33.490 --> 00:37:36.400
You know, when does the
machine blow up and run out

00:37:36.400 --> 00:37:37.130
of the space.

00:37:37.130 --> 00:37:40.680
Maybe things around usability
or accessibility, what gets

00:37:40.680 --> 00:37:42.420
loaded up first and
things like that.

00:37:42.420 --> 00:37:45.440
So we might want
to split-- I guess

00:37:45.440 --> 00:37:48.910
to me, for certain types of
permissions we prompt for today

00:37:48.910 --> 00:37:50.930
that are more around
usage and resources,

00:37:50.930 --> 00:37:52.380
it makes sense that
the browser would infer

00:37:52.380 --> 00:37:53.754
for privacy and
security reasons.

00:37:56.681 --> 00:37:58.430
JAKE ARCHIBALD: Marcos,
what kind of stuff

00:37:58.430 --> 00:38:02.080
does Firefox OS
give you by default

00:38:02.080 --> 00:38:03.362
if you're an installed app?

00:38:03.362 --> 00:38:04.695
Is there anything in particular?

00:38:04.695 --> 00:38:05.200
MARCOS CACERES:
So I'll be honest,

00:38:05.200 --> 00:38:06.894
I don't know too much
about Firefox OS,

00:38:06.894 --> 00:38:08.310
because I mostly
focus on the web.

00:38:08.310 --> 00:38:11.737
But we could ask Jonas, because
Jonas is like-- you know.

00:38:11.737 --> 00:38:12.570
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:38:18.500 --> 00:38:20.250
JAKE ARCHIBALD: I guess
a question I'd ask

00:38:20.250 --> 00:38:23.190
is how to you handle
things like disk space?

00:38:23.190 --> 00:38:25.530
Is that something that you
give the user for free?

00:38:25.530 --> 00:38:29.130
JONAS: Yeah, so our
design policy has been,

00:38:29.130 --> 00:38:30.840
once the user
installs something you

00:38:30.840 --> 00:38:34.510
get to use resources
as much as you want.

00:38:34.510 --> 00:38:36.310
You get unlimited
access to resources.

00:38:36.310 --> 00:38:41.700
So that's things like CPU
running in the background, band

00:38:41.700 --> 00:38:46.310
wave, and storing stuff to disk.

00:38:46.310 --> 00:38:48.070
And then you also get
to annoy the user.

00:38:48.070 --> 00:38:50.260
So things like,
notifications will

00:38:50.260 --> 00:38:53.430
let you do without any prompts.

00:38:53.430 --> 00:38:55.910
And the idea has
been that we give you

00:38:55.910 --> 00:38:58.702
the users all of these--
or we give applications

00:38:58.702 --> 00:39:00.910
all these things, but then
we give tools to the users

00:39:00.910 --> 00:39:02.950
so can dial it down
if they want to.

00:39:02.950 --> 00:39:05.029
So users can say, this
is very annoying app,

00:39:05.029 --> 00:39:06.820
I'm going to turn off
notifications for it,

00:39:06.820 --> 00:39:07.695
or just uninstall it.

00:39:07.695 --> 00:39:09.861
JAKE ARCHIBALD: So should
we do the same on the web?

00:39:09.861 --> 00:39:10.750
Add to home screens?

00:39:10.750 --> 00:39:12.284
Same style permissions?

00:39:12.284 --> 00:39:13.950
MARCOS CACERES: I
mean, I would say yes.

00:39:13.950 --> 00:39:15.991
Like if you're going to
do that then integrate it

00:39:15.991 --> 00:39:19.580
into the system as
much as possible.

00:39:19.580 --> 00:39:20.990
CHRIS WILSON: But it--

00:39:20.990 --> 00:39:24.010
BRIAN LEROUX: Firefox also has
three layers of apps though.

00:39:24.010 --> 00:39:28.280
There's implicit
on board blessed

00:39:28.280 --> 00:39:30.370
apps that get full
system access,

00:39:30.370 --> 00:39:33.880
then there's installed
apps from the wild,

00:39:33.880 --> 00:39:35.980
and they don't get
full system access.

00:39:35.980 --> 00:39:37.610
Isn't that the case currently?

00:39:37.610 --> 00:39:40.010
Like there's two layers?

00:39:40.010 --> 00:39:42.290
MARCOS CACERES: Hosted
apps, certified, and--

00:39:42.290 --> 00:39:43.190
BRIAN LEROUX: Yeah.

00:39:43.190 --> 00:39:44.356
JONAS: We have three levels.

00:39:44.356 --> 00:39:47.410
We have the certified
apps that are built-in.

00:39:47.410 --> 00:39:51.020
We have privileged apps which
have to be signed and reviewed

00:39:51.020 --> 00:39:52.860
by the Mozilla marketplace.

00:39:52.860 --> 00:39:55.579
And then we have
normal web apps.

00:39:55.579 --> 00:39:58.120
BRIAN LEROUX: So that's the same
as-- well it's not the same,

00:39:58.120 --> 00:39:59.911
but it's similar to
Apple's security model.

00:39:59.911 --> 00:40:01.850
There's a curation
process, which

00:40:01.850 --> 00:40:04.330
is-- I think this is the thing
that the web community is

00:40:04.330 --> 00:40:05.747
like most adverse to.

00:40:05.747 --> 00:40:07.622
You know, we don't like
the idea that there's

00:40:07.622 --> 00:40:10.000
a central place where
someone gets to curate,

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:13.150
effectively censor, what
other people get to see.

00:40:13.150 --> 00:40:16.830
And at the same time, we
don't want My Little Pony apps

00:40:16.830 --> 00:40:20.010
turning into the gambling,
porno app overnight.

00:40:20.010 --> 00:40:22.260
CHRIS WILSON: Well even more
than My Little Pony apps,

00:40:22.260 --> 00:40:24.220
which my daughter's
would love, you

00:40:24.220 --> 00:40:27.600
need the ability to have
some kind of insight

00:40:27.600 --> 00:40:30.060
into where your
disk space is going.

00:40:30.060 --> 00:40:33.200
Like particularly when we're
talking about mobile devices.

00:40:33.200 --> 00:40:37.260
That storage is still a
somewhat limited quantity.

00:40:37.260 --> 00:40:39.332
And I don't want
every application

00:40:39.332 --> 00:40:41.040
to think, yeah, it's
totally cool to dump

00:40:41.040 --> 00:40:44.099
100 gigabytes of
stuff onto my device.

00:40:44.099 --> 00:40:45.890
Because it may not be,
but at the same time

00:40:45.890 --> 00:40:47.515
there are certainly
applications that I

00:40:47.515 --> 00:40:50.960
want to be able to store
100 gigabytes of game data

00:40:50.960 --> 00:40:52.470
or whatever, and keep it there.

00:40:52.470 --> 00:40:55.220
And don't just arbitrarily
dump it out of cache

00:40:55.220 --> 00:40:56.340
because you need some.

00:40:56.340 --> 00:40:58.048
JAKE ARCHIBALD: We've
got the Cordova API

00:40:58.048 --> 00:41:00.102
and Mozilla's not too
keen on that right?

00:41:00.102 --> 00:41:01.560
MARCOS CACERES:
Not that I know of.

00:41:01.560 --> 00:41:06.080
But the thing is that
you can handle that thing

00:41:06.080 --> 00:41:07.610
in different ways, right?

00:41:07.610 --> 00:41:09.120
There are other
signals we can use.

00:41:09.120 --> 00:41:10.828
The way you don't need
to annoy the user.

00:41:10.828 --> 00:41:13.440
You can annoy the user if you
want, but you don't have to.

00:41:13.440 --> 00:41:14.900
Then there are
other places where

00:41:14.900 --> 00:41:16.733
you can go within the
device to actually see

00:41:16.733 --> 00:41:18.800
which app is actually
using up how much space.

00:41:18.800 --> 00:41:20.630
Which is what happens
in Firefox OS.

00:41:20.630 --> 00:41:25.250
And so there are various ways
to manage it that don't actually

00:41:25.250 --> 00:41:28.132
have to have an
API bound to them.

00:41:28.132 --> 00:41:30.340
JAKE ARCHIBALD: So Alex do
you have something to say?

00:41:30.340 --> 00:41:33.410
You're on that screen,
but not that screen.

00:41:33.410 --> 00:41:35.276
So do you have something to say?

00:41:39.107 --> 00:41:40.440
ALEX RUSSELL: Again, two things.

00:41:40.440 --> 00:41:44.490
So the first is that, I think,
between Marcos and Jonas

00:41:44.490 --> 00:41:47.300
we've identified a really
interesting split between, sort

00:41:47.300 --> 00:41:49.910
of the web-centric view of what
it means to have a permission,

00:41:49.910 --> 00:41:52.030
sort of ambulantly
granted, and then

00:41:52.030 --> 00:41:53.530
sort of the trust
level view of what

00:41:53.530 --> 00:41:55.210
it means to have a
permission granted.

00:41:55.210 --> 00:42:00.110
And I think, even inside
of one organization,

00:42:00.110 --> 00:42:01.760
you see multiple
opinions expressed.

00:42:01.760 --> 00:42:04.176
And I think one of the things
that we're trying to do now,

00:42:04.176 --> 00:42:07.200
in the design of new web
APIs is to make sure--

00:42:07.200 --> 00:42:11.019
and vendors, even inside
the same organization,

00:42:11.019 --> 00:42:13.310
different vendors and even
inside the same organization

00:42:13.310 --> 00:42:16.180
can express different
policies without having

00:42:16.180 --> 00:42:18.460
to agree on different APIs.

00:42:18.460 --> 00:42:20.510
So one of things
that I think people

00:42:20.510 --> 00:42:22.330
get very bound up
in is exactly what

00:42:22.330 --> 00:42:25.860
the UI for a particular
policy is going to be.

00:42:25.860 --> 00:42:28.462
But if we make these requests
for permission asynchronous,

00:42:28.462 --> 00:42:29.920
we make it the
developer's problem,

00:42:29.920 --> 00:42:30.820
on some level to deal with.

00:42:30.820 --> 00:42:32.403
And I think that's
one of the big ways

00:42:32.403 --> 00:42:33.730
out that we can evolve through.

00:42:33.730 --> 00:42:35.230
Because we don't
have agreement yet.

00:42:35.230 --> 00:42:37.670
And getting agreement is going
to require experimentation.

00:42:37.670 --> 00:42:41.580
The second side of
this is that it's

00:42:41.580 --> 00:42:44.932
one thing for Google to sort
of automatically intuit who

00:42:44.932 --> 00:42:46.140
should have what permissions.

00:42:46.140 --> 00:42:49.150
And I think that sounds very
scary to everyone including me.

00:42:49.150 --> 00:42:52.890
But we don't necessarily
feel bad about Google

00:42:52.890 --> 00:42:54.570
running the safe
browsing system.

00:42:54.570 --> 00:42:57.750
And so the idea that we're going
to be able to hit Control Z

00:42:57.750 --> 00:43:01.506
and keep users safe once we
acquire some knowledge of abuse

00:43:01.506 --> 00:43:03.880
is very different to the idea
that we're going to mediate

00:43:03.880 --> 00:43:06.340
upfront permissions,
outside of the user's intent

00:43:06.340 --> 00:43:09.390
and outside the user-presented
model of what they think

00:43:09.390 --> 00:43:11.780
is going to happen when they
decide to keep or install

00:43:11.780 --> 00:43:14.500
a particular thing, or agree
to a particular pop up.

00:43:14.500 --> 00:43:18.800
So it's good, and we
surface a bunch of the UI

00:43:18.800 --> 00:43:21.740
for mediating these permissions
once they're granted.

00:43:21.740 --> 00:43:25.480
But I think we need to
keep in mind that it's

00:43:25.480 --> 00:43:27.810
more important to be able
to hit Control Z then

00:43:27.810 --> 00:43:30.070
to mediate the upfront thing.

00:43:30.070 --> 00:43:32.090
JAKE ARCHIBALD:
So Chris Messiner,

00:43:32.090 --> 00:43:34.511
are you-- oh you got a
microphone, go for it.

00:43:34.511 --> 00:43:35.386
CHRIS MESSINER: Test.

00:43:35.386 --> 00:43:35.886
OK.

00:43:35.886 --> 00:43:39.460
So you guys are sort of
taking a look at this

00:43:39.460 --> 00:43:41.230
from the current
state of technology

00:43:41.230 --> 00:43:43.810
but we're on the cusp
of user interfaces,

00:43:43.810 --> 00:43:46.180
in particular, that don't
actually require pixels.

00:43:46.180 --> 00:43:48.370
So whether it's a
voice activated thing

00:43:48.370 --> 00:43:51.584
or you're in the car
and you're driving,

00:43:51.584 --> 00:43:53.000
or there's shared
interfaces where

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:55.290
it's more of a collaborative,
computing experience,

00:43:55.290 --> 00:43:57.950
where does all of
these problems go

00:43:57.950 --> 00:43:59.240
and how do you deal with that?

00:43:59.240 --> 00:44:01.115
What happens when there's
multiple users that

00:44:01.115 --> 00:44:01.890
are authenticated?

00:44:01.890 --> 00:44:03.848
And again, what happens
when you don't actually

00:44:03.848 --> 00:44:07.380
have pixels to display with
text for a user to read?

00:44:07.380 --> 00:44:09.150
What does that look like?

00:44:09.150 --> 00:44:13.000
CHRIS WILSON: I that's one
of the reasons why this model

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:17.340
where the developer's more
in control of when they ask

00:44:17.340 --> 00:44:19.580
the question-- when they
say to the user, hey,

00:44:19.580 --> 00:44:23.150
I want the ability
to x because y.

00:44:23.150 --> 00:44:25.412
I think that lets you
build applications

00:44:25.412 --> 00:44:26.620
that have that sort of thing.

00:44:26.620 --> 00:44:29.560
Where you don't necessarily
have a screen all the time

00:44:29.560 --> 00:44:30.740
to look at things.

00:44:30.740 --> 00:44:33.470
Now the question of, if
you never have a screen,

00:44:33.470 --> 00:44:37.760
I think that becomes even harder
and then it's sort of, well,

00:44:37.760 --> 00:44:38.810
what does that lock to?

00:44:38.810 --> 00:44:41.670
Like, at some level do you
have to have permissions

00:44:41.670 --> 00:44:43.610
that are read out to the user?

00:44:43.610 --> 00:44:46.580
If it's a voice
interaction system?

00:44:46.580 --> 00:44:48.350
Probably, unless
you've locked it

00:44:48.350 --> 00:44:52.140
to some set of the apps upfront
that are pre-authenticated,

00:44:52.140 --> 00:44:54.004
in which case, you're good.

00:44:54.004 --> 00:44:55.420
JAKE ARCHIBALD:
So with that we're

00:44:55.420 --> 00:45:00.490
going to move onto the next
question, which comes from me.

00:45:00.490 --> 00:45:03.960
Assuming we fix offline
and install-ability-- all

00:45:03.960 --> 00:45:06.127
of these problems are solved.

00:45:06.127 --> 00:45:06.960
BRIAN LEROUX: Sweet.

00:45:06.960 --> 00:45:08.440
JAKE ARCHIBALD: Yeah, great.

00:45:08.440 --> 00:45:11.410
But how do we get people
to expect them to work?

00:45:11.410 --> 00:45:15.540
How can a user expect
the web to work offline?

00:45:15.540 --> 00:45:17.064
Or have these
advanced capabilities?

00:45:17.064 --> 00:45:18.480
CHRIS WILSON: Jake,
what do thing?

00:45:18.480 --> 00:45:19.510
JAKE ARCHIBALD: I
have no idea, that's

00:45:19.510 --> 00:45:20.718
why I put the question there.

00:45:20.718 --> 00:45:23.212
I was hoping we could
sort this out right now.

00:45:23.212 --> 00:45:25.670
BRIAN LEROUX: I don't anybody's
figured this out, including

00:45:25.670 --> 00:45:26.710
native apps, right?

00:45:26.710 --> 00:45:28.210
We're still having
a lot of trouble.

00:45:28.210 --> 00:45:29.668
You can't install
an app unless you

00:45:29.668 --> 00:45:32.850
are online which is something
people seem to forget a lot.

00:45:32.850 --> 00:45:35.710
And now once you've got
that app installed-- like,

00:45:35.710 --> 00:45:38.152
even Twitter thrashers
when it's starting up.

00:45:38.152 --> 00:45:39.860
It's like, oh, what
am I doing right now?

00:45:39.860 --> 00:45:42.700
Am I loading new
stuff or am I showing

00:45:42.700 --> 00:45:44.970
you stuff that you
already had here?

00:45:44.970 --> 00:45:47.710
You have the noticeable three
second delay with Twitter.

00:45:47.710 --> 00:45:50.711
Which is probably one of the top
used apps on everybody's phone

00:45:50.711 --> 00:45:51.210
here.

00:45:51.210 --> 00:45:53.520
So what's it going to look like?

00:45:53.520 --> 00:45:54.160
I don't know.

00:45:54.160 --> 00:45:55.130
Not that.

00:45:55.130 --> 00:45:55.822
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:55.822 --> 00:45:58.280
MATT ANDREWS: Maybe this is
the developer's responsibility.

00:45:58.280 --> 00:45:59.072
Maybe this is not--

00:45:59.072 --> 00:46:00.529
JAKE ARCHIBALD:
You're a developer.

00:46:00.529 --> 00:46:03.210
MATT ANDREWS: Well, not the
browser's responsibility,

00:46:03.210 --> 00:46:04.070
our responsibility.

00:46:04.070 --> 00:46:06.780
Because it's up to us to make
a good experience, firstly.

00:46:06.780 --> 00:46:08.863
And there's no point
shouting, "it works offline,"

00:46:08.863 --> 00:46:11.485
if, when people actually come
around to using it, it doesn't.

00:46:11.485 --> 00:46:15.489
JAKE ARCHIBALD: So how did you
handle that in the FT case?

00:46:15.489 --> 00:46:17.280
MATT ANDREWS: Well, we
just shout about it.

00:46:17.280 --> 00:46:18.962
You know, it's on
all of the adverts

00:46:18.962 --> 00:46:20.170
for all of the promos for it.

00:46:20.170 --> 00:46:23.040
I mean if you've ever visited
FT.com on your mobile device,

00:46:23.040 --> 00:46:26.459
you get a big, irritating
thing that comes up and says,

00:46:26.459 --> 00:46:28.500
use our app because that's
what you'd want to do.

00:46:30.934 --> 00:46:33.350
JAKE ARCHIBALD: Did you find
users actually using offline?

00:46:33.350 --> 00:46:35.767
I guess it's difficult
to do analytics on that.

00:46:35.767 --> 00:46:37.600
MATT ANDREWS: No, we
have analytics on that.

00:46:37.600 --> 00:46:39.814
We have analytics on that.

00:46:39.814 --> 00:46:41.480
Basically we get, we
people are offline,

00:46:41.480 --> 00:46:43.240
we store in local
storage and then--

00:46:43.240 --> 00:46:43.930
JAKE ARCHIBALD: Oh, cool.

00:46:43.930 --> 00:46:45.470
MATT ANDREWS: Taking it
back when-- yeah, yeah.

00:46:45.470 --> 00:46:46.330
JAKE ARCHIBALD: You did do it?

00:46:46.330 --> 00:46:48.890
MATT ANDREWS: There are some
subtle complexities with that

00:46:48.890 --> 00:46:51.750
but, yeah, I think 20%
of traffic is offline.

00:46:51.750 --> 00:46:53.089
Or something like that.

00:46:53.089 --> 00:46:55.380
That's quite an old stat, so
it might be different now.

00:46:55.380 --> 00:46:56.570
But yeah, people use it.

00:46:56.570 --> 00:46:58.934
People complain
when we break it,

00:46:58.934 --> 00:47:00.100
which happens sometimes too.

00:47:04.094 --> 00:47:06.510
JAKE ARCHIBALD: So I know more
about the state of iOS apps

00:47:06.510 --> 00:47:08.120
than Android apps.

00:47:08.120 --> 00:47:10.520
Do the majority of
BlackBerry apps work offline?

00:47:10.520 --> 00:47:12.978
Do you find that the ones are
sort of, built in the Cordova

00:47:12.978 --> 00:47:14.465
way, are they offline capable?

00:47:14.465 --> 00:47:16.820
Is that well
communicated to the user?

00:47:16.820 --> 00:47:21.650
ELI FIDLER: I think a lot of
them are available offline.

00:47:21.650 --> 00:47:24.670
Obviously app
developers don't always

00:47:24.670 --> 00:47:25.890
do a good job about this.

00:47:25.890 --> 00:47:29.910
Even top apps often don't
do a good job with this.

00:47:29.910 --> 00:47:32.132
But for the Cordova
style case, there's

00:47:32.132 --> 00:47:34.090
something fundamental
about the technology that

00:47:34.090 --> 00:47:37.249
makes it that hard to implement
something that works offline.

00:47:37.249 --> 00:47:39.040
In the browser, that's
a different problem.

00:47:39.040 --> 00:47:41.150
We know that there's lots of
issues with the technology

00:47:41.150 --> 00:47:41.480
there.

00:47:41.480 --> 00:47:43.646
But we know that users don't
expect that [INAUDIBLE]

00:47:43.646 --> 00:47:46.456
to work offline, even
if it could today.

00:47:46.456 --> 00:47:48.845
If you hit the browser icon
people don't expect that.

00:47:48.845 --> 00:47:50.470
MATT ANDREWS: But if
we did train users

00:47:50.470 --> 00:47:52.580
to expect to use it offline,
they'd be disappointed a lot.

00:47:52.580 --> 00:47:54.246
Because I think most
websites, no matter

00:47:54.246 --> 00:47:56.380
how much we say it's
possible, most websites

00:47:56.380 --> 00:47:57.297
won't bother to do it.

00:47:57.297 --> 00:47:59.213
CHRIS WILSON: But I think
we train users today

00:47:59.213 --> 00:48:00.470
that native apps work offline.

00:48:00.470 --> 00:48:04.367
And I'm frequently
disappointed then as well.

00:48:04.367 --> 00:48:06.200
JAKE ARCHIBALD: So
you've saying the Cordova

00:48:06.200 --> 00:48:07.500
stuff doesn't work offline well?

00:48:07.500 --> 00:48:08.010
Is that your?

00:48:08.010 --> 00:48:08.968
ELI FIDLER: No it does.

00:48:08.968 --> 00:48:10.030
JAKE ARCHIBALD: It does.

00:48:10.030 --> 00:48:12.071
ELI FIDLER: The technology
makes it work offline.

00:48:12.071 --> 00:48:13.660
So then it's up to
the app developers.

00:48:13.660 --> 00:48:15.160
BRIAN LEROUX: So
this actually keyed

00:48:15.160 --> 00:48:17.201
on something that's been
bugging us a lot lately.

00:48:17.201 --> 00:48:20.140
So the way Cordova works today,
we load off the file protocol.

00:48:20.140 --> 00:48:22.900
So anything on file, colon,
slash, slash, we load it.

00:48:22.900 --> 00:48:25.870
And then WebKit has this
awesome feature, maybe a bug,

00:48:25.870 --> 00:48:30.250
that there's no content security
policy on file, colon, slash,

00:48:30.250 --> 00:48:30.750
slash.

00:48:30.750 --> 00:48:32.610
So you can load anything
from any domain,

00:48:32.610 --> 00:48:34.990
which is kind of rad.

00:48:34.990 --> 00:48:37.570
In iOS8-- Marcos
talked about this--

00:48:37.570 --> 00:48:38.770
there's this new web view.

00:48:38.770 --> 00:48:41.699
And in iOS8 we can't load off,
file, colon, slash, slash.

00:48:41.699 --> 00:48:43.990
And it's a bug, and it's been
marked in radar as a bug.

00:48:43.990 --> 00:48:46.445
So Cordova's not going to get
to use the new WK webview.

00:48:46.445 --> 00:48:48.320
Or at least that's what
I think they thought,

00:48:48.320 --> 00:48:49.921
and we thought initially.

00:48:49.921 --> 00:48:51.420
We found that there's
a work around.

00:48:51.420 --> 00:48:53.560
And interestingly,
we've had this work

00:48:53.560 --> 00:48:55.910
around for awhile in
our Android world,

00:48:55.910 --> 00:48:58.449
where we run a web
server on the phone.

00:48:58.449 --> 00:49:00.990
I know everybody's like, what
the fuck are you talking about?

00:49:00.990 --> 00:49:03.040
Run a web server on your phone?

00:49:03.040 --> 00:49:03.620
It works.

00:49:03.620 --> 00:49:06.040
And so, we can load
off a local host.

00:49:06.040 --> 00:49:08.370
But now we're running a
full fledged web server

00:49:08.370 --> 00:49:10.840
as a part of our
app on the client.

00:49:10.840 --> 00:49:14.080
And that's got implications that
I totally don't understand yet.

00:49:14.080 --> 00:49:17.250
I know Opera did it first,
if there's an Opera guy here.

00:49:17.250 --> 00:49:20.462
But it's interesting.

00:49:20.462 --> 00:49:21.920
And so I don't know
where this goes

00:49:21.920 --> 00:49:23.711
but this changes the
whole offline question

00:49:23.711 --> 00:49:26.490
all together now, because now
I'm running a fully capable web

00:49:26.490 --> 00:49:28.520
server on the device as well.

00:49:28.520 --> 00:49:30.030
JAKE ARCHIBALD: It should
have just like a proxy server,

00:49:30.030 --> 00:49:31.810
and then you could have
called it Service Worker,

00:49:31.810 --> 00:49:33.393
and then we could
put it in a browser.

00:49:33.393 --> 00:49:34.060
[LAUGHTER]

00:49:34.060 --> 00:49:34.755
BRIAN LEROUX: Well,
Service Worker

00:49:34.755 --> 00:49:37.440
is kind of like a web server-ish
interface on a phone too.

00:49:37.440 --> 00:49:39.439
So we're entering
into this world

00:49:39.439 --> 00:49:40.980
where there's web
servers everywhere.

00:49:40.980 --> 00:49:42.960
Maybe we will have the
distributed computing

00:49:42.960 --> 00:49:43.545
thing happen.

