But at the same time, the idea
that you can sanely read a URL,

00:52:45.640 --> 00:52:47.040
that time is gone.

00:52:47.040 --> 00:52:49.190
That time's been gone
for a decade or more

00:52:49.190 --> 00:52:50.920
at this point at least.

00:52:50.920 --> 00:52:54.377
And it is all junk in there
and you shouldn't read it,

00:52:54.377 --> 00:52:56.460
but it's still an identifier,
it's still something

00:52:56.460 --> 00:53:02.050
that-- I feel like in how I
internalized the UI of a web

00:53:02.050 --> 00:53:04.600
application, that's
just a little marker

00:53:04.600 --> 00:53:06.860
and it's totally opaque.

00:53:06.860 --> 00:53:08.892
It's a token identifier.

00:53:08.892 --> 00:53:10.350
It's a button that
I want to press,

00:53:10.350 --> 00:53:12.630
or something, to go back to it.

00:53:12.630 --> 00:53:15.070
But it's not actually
something I really need to see.

00:53:15.070 --> 00:53:16.695
BRIAN LEROUX: We keep
getting attracted

00:53:16.695 --> 00:53:18.790
to this idea of human readable.

00:53:18.790 --> 00:53:21.510
Remember when people said
XML is human readable?

00:53:21.510 --> 00:53:22.510
People used to say that.

00:53:22.510 --> 00:53:25.009
And then they started saying,
no, that's not human readable,

00:53:25.009 --> 00:53:25.580
JSON is.

00:53:25.580 --> 00:53:27.537
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:27.537 --> 00:53:29.370
CHRIS WILSON: You didn't
sit down last night

00:53:29.370 --> 00:53:31.371
with a big tome of XML
and just read it for fun?

00:53:31.371 --> 00:53:32.911
BRIAN LEROUX: Just
paging through it.

00:53:32.911 --> 00:53:34.250
God, this is beautiful.

00:53:34.250 --> 00:53:36.920
JAKE ARCHIBALD: Andrew's holding
a microphone, looking eager.

00:53:36.920 --> 00:53:38.795
ANDREW BETTS: So one of
the biggest arguments

00:53:38.795 --> 00:53:40.940
for the hiding of the URL
is the phishing thing.

00:53:40.940 --> 00:53:43.592
You know, that you want to
avoid users being phished

00:53:43.592 --> 00:53:45.050
by hiding the bit
of the URL that's

00:53:45.050 --> 00:53:48.545
least important in identifying
that the site is safe.

00:53:48.545 --> 00:53:50.170
And I think one of
the biggest problems

00:53:50.170 --> 00:53:52.830
with that is that it
doesn't actually work.

00:53:52.830 --> 00:53:56.350
Because you have a phone
that is small enough

00:53:56.350 --> 00:53:58.680
that it can only display
part of the host name.

00:53:58.680 --> 00:54:00.530
So what you've got
to do is register

00:54:00.530 --> 00:54:04.400
an evil dot com--
and evil dot come

00:54:04.400 --> 00:54:06.090
which has a subdomain
that looks legit

00:54:06.090 --> 00:54:07.880
and that has the same
prefix as the one

00:54:07.880 --> 00:54:09.580
that you were going
to log into anyway.

00:54:09.580 --> 00:54:12.130
So, I guess I don't
buy it, because I just

00:54:12.130 --> 00:54:14.857
don't see that the
benefit actually exists.

00:54:14.857 --> 00:54:17.190
CHRIS WILSON: I mean, this
is kind of what I was saying.

00:54:17.190 --> 00:54:22.000
It's like I need to know that
that token is mostly right.

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:24.910
Like if I'm going to
my bank's website,

00:54:24.910 --> 00:54:28.420
if I know that it says HTTPS
colon, wack, wack, www,

00:54:28.420 --> 00:54:31.100
dot Bank of America dot
com, and it's all green,

00:54:31.100 --> 00:54:35.060
and it's got the Bank of America
cert on it and everything,

00:54:35.060 --> 00:54:36.630
it's likely OK.

00:54:36.630 --> 00:54:38.770
But if I don't
see the URL today,

00:54:38.770 --> 00:54:41.300
how do I know that's
where it's going?

00:54:41.300 --> 00:54:44.680
How do I know it's not going to
evil dot-- or Bank of America

00:54:44.680 --> 00:54:47.202
dot, blah, blah, blah,
dot evil dot com?

00:54:47.202 --> 00:54:49.160
JAKE ARCHIBALD: Can I
get Charles a microphone?

00:54:49.160 --> 00:54:50.210
Where are you?

00:54:50.210 --> 00:54:51.160
Hand up?

00:54:55.910 --> 00:54:57.820
CHARLES: Hey.

00:54:57.820 --> 00:55:00.005
Oh, wow, that's very loud.

00:55:00.005 --> 00:55:03.650
So we've been talking a
little bit about permissions,

00:55:03.650 --> 00:55:04.400
about installable.

00:55:04.400 --> 00:55:06.920
I know that we've got a question
coming about fragmentation,

00:55:06.920 --> 00:55:10.980
what happens if we start doing
application installation, how

00:55:10.980 --> 00:55:13.456
that potentially
fragments the web.

00:55:17.280 --> 00:55:17.780
OK.

00:55:17.780 --> 00:55:19.570
No, that's on me.

00:55:19.570 --> 00:55:26.220
So I'm thinking about
hiding URL here.

00:55:26.220 --> 00:55:31.130
What happens if we look at
browser vendors as app stores?

00:55:31.130 --> 00:55:34.490
And is that a future
that is scary to us?

00:55:34.490 --> 00:55:38.620
Having them sort of be trusted
authority on permissions?

00:55:38.620 --> 00:55:40.850
On all of those
things that occur

00:55:40.850 --> 00:55:43.249
when we install an application.

00:55:43.249 --> 00:55:45.790
If that happens in the future,
is that scary or is that good?

00:55:45.790 --> 00:55:47.470
BRIAN LEROUX: It's happening.

00:55:47.470 --> 00:55:48.867
I mean it's already--

00:55:48.867 --> 00:55:51.450
CHRIS WILSON: --Chrome Web Store
has kind of got, for example.

00:55:51.450 --> 00:55:54.440
But I'm not sure that's the
model that we really want.

00:55:54.440 --> 00:55:57.560
I mean I work on a
browser, I've worked

00:55:57.560 --> 00:56:00.960
on other browsers in the past
and I still like the fact

00:56:00.960 --> 00:56:02.590
that they're somewhat
interchangeable.

00:56:02.590 --> 00:56:03.110
Right?

00:56:03.110 --> 00:56:07.880
I don't actually have a boatload
of Chrome Web apps installed

00:56:07.880 --> 00:56:11.690
on my machines because I
like the fact that I can use

00:56:11.690 --> 00:56:14.790
the web, and I can use
something that's like an app,

00:56:14.790 --> 00:56:16.620
but I don't have to
install something

00:56:16.620 --> 00:56:19.910
that doesn't work
if I go to my iPad

00:56:19.910 --> 00:56:23.784
and I don't have all
of that browser there.

00:56:23.784 --> 00:56:25.200
JAKE ARCHIBALD:
We also, as people

00:56:25.200 --> 00:56:28.910
who work on browsers
and developers,

00:56:28.910 --> 00:56:31.880
Are we all agreed to
the open web thing?

00:56:31.880 --> 00:56:35.520
This idea of vendors
controlling which

00:56:35.520 --> 00:56:36.970
things appear in an app store.

00:56:36.970 --> 00:56:38.886
We're all committed to
never doing-- or trying

00:56:38.886 --> 00:56:41.090
to rid the world of that, yeah?

00:56:41.090 --> 00:56:43.000
BRIAN LEROUX: I'm warming to it.

00:56:43.000 --> 00:56:44.920
And not to the current model.

00:56:44.920 --> 00:56:46.770
So I don't think,
for example, there

00:56:46.770 --> 00:56:49.207
should be these
singular app stores.

00:56:49.207 --> 00:56:50.790
But I'm warming to
the idea that there

00:56:50.790 --> 00:56:52.170
should be many app stores.

00:56:52.170 --> 00:56:54.740
Like Mozilla experimented
with the idea of federating--

00:56:54.740 --> 00:56:55.200
CHRIS WILSON: Yeah, absolutely.

00:56:55.200 --> 00:56:57.330
Like, many app stores,
I could get behind.

00:56:57.330 --> 00:56:59.820
Although it becomes
challenging to secure that.

00:56:59.820 --> 00:57:01.819
BRIAN LEROUX: It's terrible
that, for example, I

00:57:01.819 --> 00:57:02.610
trust Steam.

00:57:02.610 --> 00:57:03.760
I trust 'em.

00:57:03.760 --> 00:57:05.390
They have games, right?

00:57:05.390 --> 00:57:07.954
And I know what kind of
permissions those games need.

00:57:07.954 --> 00:57:10.120
They need full screen and
they need audio, whatever.

00:57:10.120 --> 00:57:12.850
And so I would totally
trust a Steam app store

00:57:12.850 --> 00:57:14.540
on any of my devices.

00:57:14.540 --> 00:57:17.340
And I think that's kind of
direction we're going now.

00:57:17.340 --> 00:57:20.140
Can we standardize,
federate, and open

00:57:20.140 --> 00:57:21.675
that part up is
the real question.

00:57:21.675 --> 00:57:23.990
And then what does
become of the web then?

00:57:23.990 --> 00:57:27.220
I think the web community
is afraid of app stores,

00:57:27.220 --> 00:57:29.670
rightfully, because they're
currently curation points that

00:57:29.670 --> 00:57:31.970
are centralized and
dangerous and kind of weird,

00:57:31.970 --> 00:57:33.890
because your have
Steve Jobs deciding

00:57:33.890 --> 00:57:35.480
what's appropriate content.

00:57:35.480 --> 00:57:39.224
And he's not alive anymore,
so how's that possible?

00:57:39.224 --> 00:57:40.890
JAKE ARCHIBALD: And
with that we are out

00:57:40.890 --> 00:57:42.306
of time for the
session, but we'll

00:57:42.306 --> 00:57:45.800
be able to continue discussions
in the breakout sessions later.

00:57:45.800 --> 00:57:48.947
I'd like to thank
all the panelists.

